"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525730","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-27","<p>We do not hold any information on either the number of assistance dogs in service or the number of people waiting to receive an assistance dog. Assistance dogs are trained and provided to those that need them, primarily through assistance dog charities. I will shortly be hosting a round table event with assistance dog charities and users, to discuss a variety of issues they have raised.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-27T10:53:40.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525730/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525730/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-15","Assistance Animals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of (a) assistance dogs that are in service and (b) people who are waiting for assistance dogs; and if he will take steps to ensure that demand for assistance dogs is met.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","40692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525731","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-27","<p>The information requested is not available. Children are given fixed term awards and it is the responsibility of the parent to make a new application once the award ends if the child still has additional needs as a result of disability. If a relevant change of circumstances is reported then the claim could be reassessed. Although data is held on numbers of renewals and supersessions we do not hold data on outcomes from these.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","40646","2016-06-27T14:25:28.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525731/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525731/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-15","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what percentage of disability living allowance for children re-assessments resulted in a change in the award entitlement in the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","40693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525732","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-27","<p>For Disability Living Allowance children are given fixed term awards and it is the responsibility of the parent to make a new application once the award ends if the child still has additional needs as a result of disability. If a relevant change of circumstances is reported then the claim could be reassessed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The table below shows the number of Renewal decisions cleared on an existing award and the number of Supersession decisions cleared which relate to a change of circumstance on an existing award, for the last three years.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Disability Living Allowance </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Child Renewals total clearances</p></td><td><p>54,772</p></td><td><p>68,148</p></td><td><p>69,436</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Child Supersessions total clearances</p></td><td><p>17,339</p></td><td><p>16,275</p></td><td><p>19,588</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total Child Supersessions + Renewals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>72,111</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>84,423</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>89,024</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Source</strong>: Department of Work and Pensions, Disability Living Allowance Computer System - RDA 80123 report</p><p> </p><p>This type of internal management information does not form part of the official statistics outputs that are released by the Department in accordance with the UK Statistics Authority’s Code of Practice and should be used with caution.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-27T14:45:44.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525732/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525732/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-15","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many re-assessments for people already receiving disability living allowance for children have been conducted in the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","Ochil and South Perthshire","Ms Tasmina Ahmed-Sheikh","40694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528711","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The decision to release Kneller Hall was confirmed as part of the Ministry of Defence’s land release announcement on 18 January 2016. Whilst the site will not be released before 2018, there are no plans to maintain a military presence (people permanently living and working) at the site once it has been released.</p><p> </p><p>I am keen to reinforce the Military relationship with the Kneller hall site, utilising our historic links with Twickenham Borough Council who have signed up to the Armed Forces Covenant, pledging specific support for the Armed Forces Community.</p><p> </p><p>We have also previously committed to continue to hold concerts at Kneller Hall in order to continue the association of the area with the Armed Forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-27T16:54:08.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528711/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528711/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Ministry of Defence: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans his Department has to maintain a military presence on the site of Kneller Hall in Whitton.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","905491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528712","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The United Kingdom’s continuous at sea nuclear deterrent will remain essential to our security today, and for as long as the global security situation demands.</p><p>A four-boat fleet is the minimum needed to provide the assurance that at least one submarine will always be at sea on covert patrol.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-06-27T16:32:41.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528712/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528712/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the security benefits of procuring four Successor submarines.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","905490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528713","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave earlier today to the hon. Members for Calder Valley (Craig Whittaker) and Sheffield, Heeley (Louise Haigh).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-06-27T16:32:06.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528713/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528713/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Islamic State: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the progress of the international campaign to defeat ISIS/Daesh.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","905495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528714","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>Our Armed Forces are held in the highest esteem for their discipline, conduct and representation of our country. Any form of bullying or sexual abuse is utterly contrary to their culture, values and ethos. The Ministry of Defence strives to reduce crime and behaviour that impacts on victims and operational capability.</p><p>Senior Officers and all personnel continue to reinforce the zero tolerance approach and actively counter any form of behaviour which damages the reputation of our Armed Forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-27T16:35:44.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528714/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528714/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Armed Forces: Crime Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to protect members of the armed forces from bullying, sexual abuse and other crimes.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","905488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528715","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave in the House on 18 April 2016 to Question 904485 to the hon. Member for Braintree (James Cleverly).</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-27T16:28:04.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528715/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528715/answer","PQ904485.docx","PQ904485.docx","Previous answer referred to","Previous answer referred to","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528715/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Armed Forces: Civil Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to protect the armed forces from persistent legal claims.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","905497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528716","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave earlier today to the hon. Member for East Renfrewshire (Kirsten Oswald).</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-06-27T16:33:52.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528716/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528716/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to promote the welfare of armed forces personnel.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","905494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528717","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence spends some £20 billion a year in the UK, making us British Industry’s largest single customer. Around half of this spend is in manufacturing and some £4 billion with small and medium-sized enterprises. We are determined to drive greater innovation into defence procurement, maximising opportunities for small and medium-sized businesses, investing in skills and supporting responsible exports, to help ensure we maintain a healthy and competitive UK defence sector.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-06-27T16:34:54.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528717/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528717/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Ministry of Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to support British jobs and industry through its procurement process.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","905492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528718","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave earlier today to the hon. Members for South East Cambridgeshire (Lucy Frazer) and Shrewsbury and Atcham (Daniel Kawczynski).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-06-27T16:31:13.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528718/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528718/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Defence: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate he has made of the projected increase in defence spending during this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","905493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528720","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Ministry of Defence is committed to improving the quality of Service Family Accommodation (SFA) provided to our Service personnel. 88% of SFA currently meet or exceed the decent homes standard. If a property fails to meet the standard, it will either be upgraded or disposed of.</p><p>Since financial year 2010-11 investment in housing has resulted in:</p><p>The separate installation of some 12,000 kitchens, bathrooms, or central heating systems and the insulation of 16,692 lofts.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-27T16:36:23.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528720/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528720/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-15","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to improve the standard of housing for service personnel.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","905484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528989","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>We are working closely with the Devolved Administrations and Territorial Offices, regularly meeting with officials and Ministers on levy implementation. The last Skills Ministers meeting was in February.</p><p> </p><p>We want to ensure the levy works for employers wherever they are in the UK and will be publishing further information later this month.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-28T15:25:05.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528989/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528989/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the devolved administrations on implementation of the Apprenticeship Levy.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","905554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528990","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>The Government recognises the importance of broadband access throughout the UK for businesses of all sizes. Under the Broadband Connection Voucher Scheme, over 50,000 SMEs across 52 cities took a connection voucher, with around 41,000 businesses already connected to super and ultra-fast broadband.</p><p>The Government is also undertaking a Review into Business Broadband, jointly led by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and the Department for Culture, Media and Sport, to explore the barriers faced by businesses, including SMEs, in accessing the affordable, high-speed broadband they need. That Review is ongoing and will report later this year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-28T15:23:26.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528990/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528990/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Broadband: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps the Government is taking to improve broadband access for small businesses.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","905555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528991","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>This Government has taken unprecedented action to help our steel industry.</p><p> </p><p>We’re cutting electricity costs by hundreds of millions, tackling unfair trade and are the first EU country to introduce new flexibility in public procurement.</p><p> </p><p>We have also offered an unparalleled package of support to secure the long term future of Tata Steel’s UK operations.</p><p> </p><p>That is what the steel industry has asked for and that is what we are delivering.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-28T15:31:09.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528991/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528991/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to support British steelmaking.","false","Biography information for Glyn Davies","Montgomeryshire","Glyn Davies","905557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528992","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>We recently consulted options for the Land Registry.</p><p> </p><p>This consultation closed on 26 May and Government are currently reviewing the responses.</p><p> </p><p>Until this is completed, no decision will be made.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Bromsgrove","Sajid Javid",,"2016-06-28T15:28:41.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528992/answer","Biography information for Sajid Javid","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528992/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Land Registry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his plans are for the future of the Land Registry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","905556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528993","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>My Department does not intervene in the billing arrangements of individual businesses in the regulated utilities.</p><p> </p><p>But I understand that most utility and other providers give customers the option to receive bills in paper form if they so request.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-28T15:35:18.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528993/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528993/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that customers are able to receive utility and other bills in paper form on request.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","905552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528994","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>We are taking action to make it quick and easy to switch suppliers. Last year, we published six switching principles, urging industry to improve their processes.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has challenged the mobile phone operators to unlock handsets for free, and the major operators have committed to doing so.</p><p> </p><p>We are also legislating for easier switching in the communications markets in the Digital Economy Bill.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-28T15:26:57.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528994/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528994/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Consumers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to facilitate customers switching suppliers in consumer markets.","false","Biography information for Jake Berry","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","905549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528995","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p>The English Apprenticeships 2020 Vision document that we published in December outlines our plans to increase the quantity and quality of apprenticeships in England.</p><p> </p><p>Employer-led reforms are making it easier and more attractive for employers to offer apprenticeships. We have also set new expectations for the public sector and through public procurement.</p><p> </p><p>We announced a £10 million fund to help boost the number of degree apprenticeships that provide the high level skills our economy needs.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-28T15:41:58.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528995/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528995/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the Government's strategy is for increasing the number of apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","905550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528996","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-28","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The hon Member recently tabled a Named Day question on this matter.</p><p> </p><p>In my answer of 13 June I advised that this was the operational responsibility of the Post Office and I would ask its Chief Executive, Paula Vennells, to write to the hon Member.</p><p> </p><p>I understand Paula Vennells wrote to the hon Member on 21 June. This letter has been placed in the Libraries of the House.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-28T15:40:07.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528996/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528996/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-15","Post Offices: Paisley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Post Office has spent on refurbishing the Crown Post Office premises in Paisley since January 2010.","false","Biography information for Mhairi Black","Paisley and Renfrewshire South","Mhairi Black","905548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529339","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>If there is a face of poverty, it is often a young face, and young people are at the heart of DFID’s agenda. We combat poverty, and religious fundamentalism, by investing in young people and their future, which is why our focus on education is so important.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-06-29T13:32:38.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529339/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529339/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Developing Countries: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what programmes her Department supports related to children and religious fundamentalism; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Graham Allen","Nottingham North","Mr Graham Allen","905515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529340","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>In 2016 DFID support in South Sudan has contributed to 2.3 million people receiving life-saving humanitarian assistance. Our education programmes have enabled 120,000 girls to complete primary education and provided 9.2 million textbooks. DFID’s Health Pooled Fund has provided primary care treatment to 8.7 million people.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-06-29T15:55:17.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529340/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529340/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","South Sudan: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of her Department's work in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","905513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529341","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>The UK is strongly committed to providing education for girls. The UK’s flagship Girls’ Education Challenge (GEC) programme is the world’s largest global fund dedicated to girls’ education. UKAID has supported over 6.6 million girls in developing countries to receive a quality education, of whom 1.6 million were at particularly high risk of missing out.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T16:01:06.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529341/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529341/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support the education of girls in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","905516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529342","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>DFID’s bilateral aid to Sri Lanka ended in 2006 when middle income status was achieved. We continue to support them through multilateral organisations and through centrally managed DFID programmes. In 2014 these amounted to at least £28m.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T14:27:14.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529342/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529342/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Sri Lanka: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department is providing to Sri Lanka.","false","Biography information for Wes Streeting","Ilford North","Wes Streeting","905514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529343","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>Since 2014 the UK has been the fourth-largest provider of humanitarian assistance to vulnerable people affected by the crisis in Ukraine.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T14:24:11.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529343/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529343/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Ukraine: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance her Department has provided to separatist occupied areas of eastern Ukraine in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","905517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529344","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>To date, we have allocated £561 million to support people inside Syria. By May 2016, this had provided 16.3 million food rations; access to clean water for 2 million people; 3.5 million medical consultations; 5.1 million relief packages; and 8.3 million sanitation and hygiene activities.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T14:25:18.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529344/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529344/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of UK aid in Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","905519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529345","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>The Global Goals were a historic global agreement to eradicate extreme poverty and achieve sustainable development. DFID is working closely with the Cabinet Office and other departments to ensure a joined-up approach to implementing the Goals. The Government will produce a report on the UK’s contribution to implementation this year.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T16:04:05.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529345/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529345/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure cross-departmental coordination of implementation of the Sustainable Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","905521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529346","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>The National Council for Voluntary Organisations, backed by the Charity Commission, has encouraged more transparency on pay issues and introduced new pay guidelines. DFID Ministers have consistently demanded that NGOs are transparent and open with donors and the public.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T16:02:01.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529346/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529346/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Non-governmental Organisations: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what representations she has made to non-governmental organisations which receive funding from her Department on senior management salaries in those organisations.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","905518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529347","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-29","<p>The commitments agreed at the London Summit could potentially achieve major benefits for developing countries including preventing their resources from being stolen and hidden abroad; ensuring international systems recover these funds whilst punishing perpetrators; and helping citizens have greater opportunities to seek justice against corruption.</p>","New Forest West","Sir Desmond Swayne",,"2016-06-29T14:26:17.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529347/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/529347/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-15","Developing Countries: Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the outcomes of the Anti-Corruption Summit in May 2016 on developing countries.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","905520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524899","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that everyone with the potential has the opportunity to benefit from higher education, irrespective of their background or mode of learning. In the last academic year we saw record entry rates to higher education, including among those from disadvantaged backgrounds. <br></p><p>Higher Education Institutions have responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 to support their students, including those with disabilities. They have a clear legal duty to make reasonable adjustments for disabled people to ensure they are not placed at a substantial disadvantage compared to non-disabled students.</p><p>Universities expect to spend more than £745 million through access agreements agreed with the Director of Fair Access on measures to improve access and success for students from disadvantaged groups, including disabled students - up significantly from £404 million in 2009.</p><p>In addition, to support Higher Education (HE) providers to prepare for the changes to Disabled Students’ Allowances that come into effect from academic year 2016/17, the Department has supported the establishment of a sector-led group of stakeholders. The group’s focus is to communicate with senior leaders of HE providers, to help provide information about institutions’ responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 to make reasonable adjustments, and to encourage HE providers to develop inclusive learning environments.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","40492","2016-06-27T08:39:51.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524899/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524899/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to increase accessibility to university buildings for disabled students.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","40494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524900","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that everyone with the potential has the opportunity to benefit from higher education, irrespective of their background or mode of learning. In the last academic year we saw record entry rates to higher education, including among those from disadvantaged backgrounds. <br></p><p>Higher Education Institutions have responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 to support their students, including those with disabilities. They have a clear legal duty to make reasonable adjustments for disabled people to ensure they are not placed at a substantial disadvantage compared to non-disabled students.</p><p>Universities expect to spend more than £745 million through access agreements agreed with the Director of Fair Access on measures to improve access and success for students from disadvantaged groups, including disabled students - up significantly from £404 million in 2009.</p><p>In addition, to support Higher Education (HE) providers to prepare for the changes to Disabled Students’ Allowances that come into effect from academic year 2016/17, the Department has supported the establishment of a sector-led group of stakeholders. The group’s focus is to communicate with senior leaders of HE providers, to help provide information about institutions’ responsibilities under the Equality Act 2010 to make reasonable adjustments, and to encourage HE providers to develop inclusive learning environments.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","40494","2016-06-27T08:39:51.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524900/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524900/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Students: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that universities are offering disabled students appropriate levels of support.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","40492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524901","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) is independent of Government. The timing of CMA publications is a matter for the CMA, taking into account its statutory deadlines.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","40500","2016-06-27T16:13:40.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524901/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524901/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations officials, advisers and Ministers of his Department made to the Competition and Markets Authority on the date of publication of its final report on the energy market.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","40499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524902","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) is independent of Government. The timing of CMA publications is a matter for the CMA, taking into account its statutory deadlines.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","40499","2016-06-27T16:13:40.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524902/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524902/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether he or any of his Ministerial colleagues were consulted by the Competition and Markets Authority on the date upon which it plans to publish its investigation into the energy market.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","40500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524903","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-29","<p>This is a complicated issue and we are considering the most appropriate way to ensure more transparency.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-29T09:55:11.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524903/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524903/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will conduct a review into the effect of the use of payment intermediaries on pay transparency before the end of 2016.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","40487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524904","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-30","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) is in line with the Civil Service Talent Action Plan, refreshed in March 2016. The Plan commits departments to actions that aim to remove barriers to success faced by underrepresented groups. The Department is committed to promoting a culture of inclusivity which celebrates, respects and encourages diversity in its workforce and recognises the benefits a diverse workforce provides and the improved business practices this can create.</p><p>BIS’ commitment to building a diverse workforce is demonstrated by activities such as supporting staff on Civil Service diversity talent schemes and establishing an internal diversity mentoring programme. The Department has undertaken an extensive internal communications campaign to build awareness and promote inclusivity. The Department has appointed a Board level Diversity Champion and director-level champions. The champions are responsible for promoting diversity issues, acting as a senior role model and providing strategic support to colleagues and internal staff networks.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-06-30T15:33:20.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524904/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524904/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Civil Servants: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39321, what progress his Department has made on plans to diversify the civil service.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","40488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524905","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are implementing a package of measures to support a cultural change to tackle late payment, including the Small Business Commissioner, the duty for large businesses to report on payment practices and support for the voluntary Prompt Payment Code. The Regulations to give effect to the duty to report will be laid for debate early in 2017.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-27T11:42:22.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524905/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524905/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Business: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to tackle late payment of suppliers by businesses.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","40643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524906","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Extractives Industry Transparency Initiative (EITI) requires implementing countries to form a Multi-Stakeholder Group (MSG) consisting of industry, civil society and government, who work in partnership to implement EITI. The MSG meets every 2 months with the next meeting on 12 July.</p><p>The UK MSG is currently reviewing the first year’s report and these recommendations form part of that review.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-06-27T11:49:19.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524906/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524906/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to implement the recommendations in the first report of the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative, published in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524907","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>There is no maximum duration for Degree Apprenticeships. The pattern of delivery of the degree will be a key component in the length of a Degree Apprenticeship, both employers and Higher Education providers will want to ensure the apprenticeship standard is achieved in full.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-27T15:11:44.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524907/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524907/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Apprentices: Degrees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the maximum duration should be for a degree apprenticeship.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","40634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524908","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>We want to increase the quantity and quality of all apprenticeships, including for people from Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic communities.</p><p> </p><p>Our far-reaching reforms are improving the quality of all apprenticeships. We have insisted that they must all be paid jobs with substantial training, develop transferable skills and have a minimum 12 months’ duration. The Institute for Apprenticeships is being created to ensure the quality of apprenticeship standards in England.</p><p> </p><p>Information on apprenticeship completion rates is published in the National Achievement Rate Tables: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sfa-national-achievement-rates-tables-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/sfa-national-achievement-rates-tables-2014-to-2015</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-27T15:13:40.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524908/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524908/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Apprentices: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to reduce the gap in apprenticeship completion rates for people who are Black, Asian and Minority Ethnic.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","40636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524909","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-06-27","<p>The apprenticeship levy will fund growth in apprenticeships at all levels, including Degree Apprenticeships. Degree Apprenticeships are widening access to the professions and providing higher level technical skills employers need.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-06-27T16:09:00.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524909/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524909/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-06-14","Apprentices: Degrees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his policy is on whether the cost of degree apprenticeships are supported from the proceeds of the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","40637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524910","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>UK law enforcement agencies​ already have strong collaborative partnerships with many overseas authorities which are valuable in supporting and developing their investigations into international corruption. The London Anti-Corruption Summit in May galvanised further efforts to improve international cooperation.</p><p>At the Summit, the PM announced that the UK will host a new International Anti-Corruption Coordination Centre (IACCC) to help law enforcement investigators work together effectively across multiple jurisdictions, ending the impunity often associated with grand corruption. We are working with international partners towards making the IACCC operational by April 2017.</p><p>The UK also committed to supporting the creation of a Centre of Excellence for Financial Intelligence Units to support the sharing of information with other countries. This will help to improve the effectiveness of the international response to international money-laundering. We are also working with other countries to establish a Global Forum for Asset Recovery.</p><p>Initiatives to enhance transparency over beneficial ownership information will also support international law enforcement cooperation in tackling international corruption. This includes the initiative on the automatic exchange of beneficial ownership information between jurisdictions, as well as the UK's new public register of persons of significant control, (which goes live this month) and the agreements reached with relevant Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies to grant UK law enforcement access to beneficial ownership information there.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:21:55.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524910/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524910/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what processes are in place for strengthening partnerships between law enforcement agencies in the UK and elsewhere in order to tackle international corruption.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524911","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>Ahead of the Anti-Corruption Summit, Cabinet Office and a number of other government departments engaged with a wide range of businesses, including professional service companies, to understand their views, promote best practice and encourage their support for the objectives of the Summit.</p><p>A number of business leaders attended the Summit, as well as the Tackling Corruption Together conference which was organised by civil society and business on 11 May. A group of professional services companies published a statement on 11 May in which they commit to maintaining robust procedures when taking on new clients and​ building ​a culture​, through education and training,​ that allows no space for corruption.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:19:33.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524911/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524911/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what discussions his Department had with business and professional services companies before the Anti-Corruption Summit on 12 May 2016.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524912","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>Yes.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:18:26.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524912/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524912/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether there is a designated team of staff in his Department working solely on anti-corruption issues.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524913","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>Agreement has been reached with all the relevant Overseas Territories, and with the Isle of Man and Jersey on the establishment of central registers or similarly effective systems. These arrangements will give UK law enforcement and tax authorities quick and unrestricted access to beneficial ownership information on corporate and legal entities incorporated in these Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies. This is a significant step forward in our ability to fight criminal activity. The signing of a similar arrangement with Guernsey is expected shortly, following their recent general election and formation of a new government.</p><p>Requests from UK law enforcement will be processed within 24 hours and quicker in urgent cases. The new arrangements must be in place by June 2017, but relevant Government Departments and law enforcement authorities are working with the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies to ensure some changes are made immediately.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-06-27T13:00:31.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524913/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524913/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what progress he has made since the Anti-Corruption Summit of 12 May 2016 on implementing the Government's plan to establish central registers of beneficial ownership in the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524915","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>This is available on www.gov.uk</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:19:53.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524915/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524915/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Anti-corruption Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will publish the terms of reference for the Inter-Ministerial Group on Anti-Corruption.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524916","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office leads on discussions with the Overseas Territories. The Ministry of Justice is responsible for the constitutional relationship with the Crown Dependencies.</p><p>Discussions on beneficial ownership information-sharing, with both the OTs and CDs, has involved a range of departments, including FCO, MoJ, HM Treasury, Cabinet Office and law enforcement authorities.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:20:13.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524916/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524916/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, who is leading the negotiations with the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies on sharing beneficial ownership information.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524917","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are currently recruiting three new board members for the Charity Commission in England and Wales, including a replacement for Peter Clarke. We are specifically seeking skills and experience in the charity sector, in law enforcement and in IT. The posts were opened for applications in early June and we intend to appoint as soon as this process is successfully concluded. The recruitment process follows the Commissioner for Public Appointments’ Code of Practice for Ministerial Appointments to Public Bodies and its core principles of merit, openness and fairness.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-06-27T07:24:26.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524917/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524917/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-14","Charity Commission: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans he has to appoint a new Charity Commissioner to replace Peter Clarke.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524918","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-29","<p>The Government is committed to increasing competition in banking to ensure banks have to work hard to offer the best possible products and services to their customers. A key part of that is making the process for customers switching their current accounts as easy and as effective as possible, to ensure customers are able to hold their banks to account by voting with their feet.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has already undertaken a lot of work to improve the process for customers switching their current accounts, including helping to deliver the Current Account Switch Service to enable customers to switch banks simply, quickly and reliably, and delivering midata, to enable customers to compare which bank is best for them based on how they use their current account.</p><p> </p><p>As part of its retail banking market investigation, the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) is considering what additional improvements could be made to the process of customers switching current accounts, including requiring banks to make historical transaction data available and making it easier for customers to switch their overdraft when they move banks. The CMA is also considering other additional measures designed to support overdraft users.</p><p> </p><p>The Government welcomes the CMA’s investigation, and stands ready to take action as necessary once it publishes its final report in the summer.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-29T13:04:59.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524918/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524918/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will discuss with the banking sector steps to ensure that individuals seeking to switch their current account are able to access their historical transaction data to better enable them to secure a similar overdraft to their existing one with a new provider.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","40577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524919","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-29","<p>The government is committed to improving financial capability among the public and recognises that increased financial capability for consumers will lead to better outcomes for both individuals and the wider economy. Helping hard-working people achieve their aspirations at every stage of their lives is at the heart of our long term plan. That is why we launched the Public Financial Guidance consultation in Budget 2016 to seek input on what role the government should play in promoting financial capability<strong>,</strong> and how the public provision of free-to-client, impartial financial guidance should be structured to give consumers the information they need to make financial decisions. The consultation closed on 8 June. The government is currently considering the responses and will respond in the Autumn. The government recognises the importance of giving young people the skills they need to make financial decisions, which is why financial education has been on the national secondary school curriculum in England since September 2014.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","40579","2016-06-29T13:02:22.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524919/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524919/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Money Advice Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether any of the successor organisations to the Money Advice Service will have a specific remit to promote financial education amongst young people.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","40576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524920","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-29","<p>The government is committed to improving financial capability among the public and recognises that increased financial capability for consumers will lead to better outcomes for both individuals and the wider economy. Helping hard-working people achieve their aspirations at every stage of their lives is at the heart of our long term plan. That is why we launched the Public Financial Guidance consultation in Budget 2016 to seek input on what role the government should play in promoting financial capability<strong>,</strong> and how the public provision of free-to-client, impartial financial guidance should be structured to give consumers the information they need to make financial decisions. The consultation closed on 8 June. The government is currently considering the responses and will respond in the Autumn. The government recognises the importance of giving young people the skills they need to make financial decisions, which is why financial education has been on the national secondary school curriculum in England since September 2014.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","40576","2016-06-29T13:02:22.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524920/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524920/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Money Advice Service","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether any successor organisations to the Money Advice Service will have a remit to promote financial capability amongst the public.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","40579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524921","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that insurance markets operate on the basis of fair and open competition.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has established the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) to promote competition for the benefit of consumers and investigates any issues that may arise in this respect, including in insurance markets.</p><p> </p><p>In 2014, the CMA investigated the competitiveness of the UK private motor insurance. It found evidence that there was strong price competition for motor insurance sold via price comparison websites (PCWs), which are responsible for over half of insurers’ new motor insurance business, and that PCWs had increased competition between private motor insurance providers overall.</p><p> </p><p>Prudential Regulation Authority (PRA) data on “net combined ratios” of motor insurers provides further indication that there is strong competition in the private motor insurance market.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills also found that the private motor insurance has high switching rates compared to other markets, providing another indicator of strong competition.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-27T10:32:32.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524921/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524921/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 18 January 2016 to Question 20373, what criteria he has used to assess the level of competitiveness in the motor insurance market.","true","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","40503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524922","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Cities and Local Growth Unit is a joint BIS-DCLG team that supports places in developing and agreeing devolution deals with the Government. Six Senior Civil Servants out of ten in the Unit are based in London.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-27T12:28:48.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524922/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524922/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-14","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 7 June 2016 to Question 39850, what proportion of the senior civil servants in the Cities and Local Growth Unit of his Department are working on devolution issues are based in London.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524923","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-27","<p>The current numbers and location of Cities and Local Growth Unit officials based in the six local teams are set out in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-06-27T12:28:24.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524923/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524923/answer","160620 - HCPQ40530.doc","160620 - HCPQ40530.doc","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524923/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-14","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39850, what the (a) location and (b) number at each location is of the 60 officials based in six local teams across the country.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","40530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524924","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-29","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that sustainable development should be at the heart of planning, and should be pursued in a positive and integrated way. It makes it clear that policies set out in paragraphs 18 to 219, taken as a whole, constitute the Government's view of what sustainable development in England means in practice for the planning system – both in preparing local plans and taking decisions on individual planning applications. It is for the decision-maker to take these policies into account when considering applications for development.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-29T14:27:52.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524924/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524924/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524924/answer/previousversion/5013","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-14","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to paragraph 7 on page 2 of the National Planning Policy Framework, published in March 2012 whether his Department has made an assessment of the extent to which the UK's carbon budgets and 2050 climate target is taken into account by planning authorities when making planning decisions.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524925","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-29","<p>Secretary of State planning casework decisions are taken on the basis of the material considerations before the Secretary of State.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-06-29T14:29:18.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524925/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524925/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-14","Fracking: Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will wait until the Committee on Climate Change report on the compatibility of UK onshore petroleum with meeting UK carbon budgets and the Government's response is published before taking any decision to reverse (a) the planning decision against fracking made by Lancashire County Council and (b) any other planning decisions that are made by local authorities concerning the extraction of shale gas.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","40551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524926","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-29","<p>This Government does not set national housing targets. The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that Local Plans should meet the full, objectively assessed needs for housing in the housing market area, as far as is consistent with the policies set out in the Framework. As part of this, local authorities should identify, and update annually, a supply of specific deliverable sites sufficient to provide five years of housing against their housing requirements. Local authorities also have a duty to cooperate on strategic planning priorities such as providing the homes that are needed.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","40989","2016-06-29T14:31:41.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524926/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524926/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-14","Local Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what requirements his Department places on local authorities to demonstrate that their Local Plans will meet identified national house-building need.","false","Biography information for Michael Tomlinson","Mid Dorset and North Poole","Michael Tomlinson","40585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524927","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government is taking forward a range of legislative measures to tackle nuisance calls and text messages, which will increase consumer protection and choice by strengthening the Information Commissioner's Office's (ICO) ability to take enforcement action against organisations that break the law. Specific actions include; strengthening the ICO's direct marketing guidance by giving it statutory status; and exploring extending the ICO’s powers of compulsory audit to more of the organisations that generate nuisance calls. This is in addition to action the Government has already taken against nuisance calls, including lowering the legal threshold for ICO action against nuisance callers and lifting the cap on fines ICO issue to companies breaking the rules. Recently a record high £200,000 fine was issued, and between the 2010 - 2015, the average fine has been £85,000 - considerably higher than in 2010, when fines were capped at £5,000.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-27T11:10:45.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524927/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524927/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-14","Nuisance Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to tackle nuisance calls and text messages.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","40601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524928","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport did not meet with the Minister for the Cabinet Office to discuss Channel 4 between 4 September 2015 and 24 September 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-27T14:22:22.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524928/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524928/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-14","Channel Four Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he met the Minister for the Cabinet Office to examine the options for extracting greater public value from Channel 4 between 4 September 2015 and 24 September 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","40504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524929","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>As part of the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review, we are reviewing a series of options that may change the way we provide our policing and guarding at some sites. Further work is required to assess the feasibility and implementation of these options and, at the appropriate time, we will initiate formal consultation with the Ministry of Defence Police staff associations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-27T15:48:18.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524929/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524929/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Ministry of Defence Police: Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to review the role of the Ministry of Defence Police in safeguarding the Trident nuclear deterrent.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","40484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524930","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The infrastructure and facilities investments being made at the Barrow-in-Furness and Faslane sites are for all our submarines not just the Successor programme. I am withholding internal Ministry of Defence forecasts on future programme expenditure as disclosure would or would be likely to prejudice on-going commercial negotiations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","40506 ; 40507 ; 40508","2016-06-27T15:29:23.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524930/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524930/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Trident Submarines: Barrow in Furness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much the budgeted expenditure is in (a) 2016-17 and (b) 2017-18 on facility improvements at Faslane to support the Trident renewal programme.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","40509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524931","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-28","<p>The UK Armed Forces have continued to play a full part in the Global Counter-Daesh Coalition programme to build the capacity of Iraqi (including Kurdish) security forces. Over the past 12 months, we have contributed to the training of over 13,600 Iraqi army personnel and some 2,570 Peshmerga, to build vital counter-IED expertise and to enhance medical and infantry skills. The impact of this training can be seen in the success of Iraqi security forces over the past year in taking back territory previously held by Daesh. Some 40% of occupied territory has now been recovered. In terms of logistic support, following the UK's substantial contributions of non-lethal support, heavy machine guns, ammunition and military equipment to meet immediate Kurdish Peshmerga needs in early 2015, the UK has provided airlift to facilitate other international contributions and, subject to parliamentary approval, is planning to provide a further £1 million of ammunition later this summer for Peshmerga use.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-28T15:09:03.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524931/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524931/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Iraq: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what training and logistical support the armed forces have provided to Iraqi forces to combat the threat from Daesh in Iraq in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","40486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524932","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>The infrastructure and facilities investments being made at the Barrow-in-Furness and Faslane sites are for all our submarines not just the Successor programme. I am withholding internal Ministry of Defence forecasts on future programme expenditure as disclosure would or would be likely to prejudice on-going commercial negotiations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","40507 ; 40508 ; 40509","2016-06-27T15:29:23.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524932/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524932/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Trident Submarines: Barrow in Furness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much has been invested in facilities at Barrow-in-Furness to support the Trident renewal programme in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","40506"
