"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524935","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-27","<p>In 2016 the UK's contribution to the Very High Readiness Joint Task Force (Maritime) will include a Maritime Commander (Rear Admiral) with 150 staff embarked in a Landing Platform Helicopter (HMS Ocean), one Type 23 Frigate for six months from January to July, one Type 45 Destroyer for up to seven weeks in the autumn and one Mine Countermeasures Vessel. In 2017, the UK's contribution will be a Commander (Commodore) and Type 45 Destroyer for six months, an ECHO Class Survey Ship (in a command role) plus one Mine Countermeasures Vessel.</p><p>Throughout 2016 and 2017, the UK's contribution to the Very High Readiness Joint Task Force (Air) will include six Tornados and six Typhoons, Airborne Early Warning and Air to Air refueling aircraft.</p><p> </p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-06-27T15:31:36.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524935/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524935/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","NATO: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will provide details of what (a) ships and (b) aircraft by (i) type and (ii) number are allocated to the Very High Readiness Task Force in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","40549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524936","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-28","<p>Primary healthcare for serving Armed Forces personnel is provided by the Defence Medical Services (DMS).</p><p>Leaflet 1-3-4 of Joint Service Publication 950 (the Defence medical policy document) explains the healthcare transition arrangements for personnel leaving the Services and DMS care. This includes information on registering with an NHS General Practitioner.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-06-28T15:13:12.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524936/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524936/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Armed Forces: General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent guidelines he has issued to members of the armed forces on registering with a doctor.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","40612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524937","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-28","<p>Her Majesty's Government provides educational training to the Burmese military. In 2015 this included the Managing Defence in a Wider Security Context and Strategic Leadership Programmes, both delivered by the Defence Academy of the United Kingdom in partnership with Cranfield University. In addition, the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst delivered a Psychology of Leadership programme in Burma, and we have also provided English language training. Both programmes delivered by the Defence Academy included dedicated modules on Human Rights and International Humanitarian Law. Ethics in Leadership and the issue of Child Soldiers and Women and Girls in Conflict Zones are also included in the syllabus. The Government does not provide any form of combat training to the Burmese army.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-28T15:10:38.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524937/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524937/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524937/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-14","Burma: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assistance, education and training the Government is providing to the Burmese Army; and whether the Government provides training on human rights and humanitarian obligations.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524938","Department for Education","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Department publishes statutory guidance (for schools which sets a clear framework for the provision of careers advice and guidance. The guidance, which is available at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/440795/Careers_Guidance_Schools_Guidance.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/440795/Careers_Guidance_Schools_Guidance.pdf</a> sets out how every school should engage with local employers and professionals to ensure real-world connections are in place to prepare young people for working life. These activities could include speakers from the world of work, mentoring, workplace visits or help with basic career management skills like CV writing.</p><p> </p><p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) continues to make excellent progress. Its Enterprise Adviser Network is brokering links between schools, colleges and employers in 36 Local Enterprise Partnership areas; with 60 Enterprise Coordinators and 400 Enterprise Advisers working with schools and colleges to support their careers and enterprise provision. In March 2016 The CEC announced 33 successful bidders to its £5m careers and enterprise fund. This £5m investment from government will boost provision for nearly 250,000 young people across England in 75% of the areas the company has identified as ‘cold spots’. In addition, the company is working to create a new generation of high-quality mentors to help teenagers fulfil their potential.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-06-27T08:45:32.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524938/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524938/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-14","School Leaving: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure that all 18 year olds leaving school have the skills to prepare a high quality CV.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","40527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524939","Department for Education","false","2016-06-27","<p>It is for admission authorities to decide, in light of their local circumstances, how best to fulfil the duty set out in the School Admissions Code to consult on their admission arrangements.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-27T15:06:56.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524939/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524939/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-14","Academies: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 27 May 2016 to Question 37443, what guidance her Department provides to school admission authorities on engaging with those people that the Schools Admissions Code requires them to consult.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","40533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524940","Department for Education","false","2016-06-27","<p>These are matters for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-27T15:05:57.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524940/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524940/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-14","Ofsted: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what procedures her Department has in place to scrutinise any possible conflicts of interest that Ofsted inspectors may have when inspecting primary schools; how many Ofsted inspectors are involved in the conversion of primary schools to academies in either an advisory or developmental capacity; and whether Ofsted inspectors are required to inform head teachers that they have an interest in the development of academies prior to conducting an inspection.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","40495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524941","Department for Education","false","2016-06-27","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-06-27T15:06:18.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524941/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524941/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-14","Ofsted: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether Ofsted inspectors are required to have experience of teaching in primary schools prior to becoming an inspector.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","40496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524942","Department for Education","false","2016-06-27","<p>As set out in my answer to questions 39845 and 40028, we are currently investigating institutions that may be operating as unregistered independent schools in England. The actual number under investigation fluctuates all the time as new settings come to our attention and existing ones close, or are confirmed not to be operating as schools. We will make a statement about progress in due course.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-06-27T15:03:20.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524942/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524942/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-06-14","Out-of-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 8 June 2016 to Question 40028, on investigations into unregistered schools, how many investigations her Department is currently carrying out into unregistered schools in England.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","40497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524943","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Department will be providing a Government response to the Competition and Market Authority’s final publication on the energy market in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:03:36.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524943/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524943/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she plans to make a statement to the House on the publication of the final report into the energy market from the Competition and Markets Authority.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","40501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524944","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) are an independent body and the date of publication of their reports is their decision. Officials, Advisors and Ministers in the Department have not made any representations to the CMA, and the CMA have not consulted Ministers or advisors, on the date of the publication of this report. Officials in my Department have discussed with the CMA their intended date of publication for final report on the energy market to inform the Department’s own planning.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","40518","2016-06-27T09:04:12.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524944/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524944/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what representations officials, advisers and Ministers in her Department made to the Competition and Markets Authority on the date of publication of its final report on the energy market.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","40517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524945","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) are an independent body and the date of publication of their reports is their decision. Officials, Advisors and Ministers in the Department have not made any representations to the CMA, and the CMA have not consulted Ministers or advisors, on the date of the publication of this report. Officials in my Department have discussed with the CMA their intended date of publication for final report on the energy market to inform the Department’s own planning.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","40517","2016-06-27T09:04:12.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524945/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524945/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she or any of her ministerial colleagues were consulted by the Competition and Markets Authority on the date on which it plans to publish its investigation into the energy market.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","40518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524946","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>Further to the Answer to Question 39080, we are continuing to consider the report and will lay it before Parliament with our response in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:07:10.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524946/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524946/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Oil: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 23 May 2016 to Question 39080, if she will make it her  policy to lay the Committee on Climate Change report on the compatibility of UK onshore petroleum with meeting UK carbon budgets and the Government's response before Parliament prior to any decision is taken to reverse (a) the planning decision against fracking made by Lancashire County Council and (b) any other planning decisions that are made by local authorities concerning the extraction of shale gas.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","40552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524947","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>We see the use of conversions of coal to biomass as a transitional technology. It has played a useful role in decarbonising the grid while other, lower carbon forms of energy generation, such as offshore wind continue to develop and lower their costs. Government support for biomass conversions are restricted to 2027 under the Renewables Obligation and Contract for Difference, however all other biomass technologies are eligible for the full 15 year life of the contract. We have no current plans to change those dates.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:06:11.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524947/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524947/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what consideration she has given to extending the support of biomass after 2027 to treat it equally with other low-carbon technologies.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","40554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524948","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Civil Nuclear Constabulary May 2015 Wellbeing Survey is a document owned by the Civil Nuclear Constabulary. It’s a matter for the CNC whether to publish the survey.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:07:31.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524948/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524948/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Civil Nuclear Constabulary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 9 June 2016 to Question 39039, whether she will place the results of the Civil Nuclear Constabulary May 2015 Wellbeing Survey in the Library.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","40555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524949","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>The next review of the Coal Authority will take place towards the end of the current Parliament at a time to be confirmed. It will be based on guidance for tailored reviews of public bodies published in March 2016 that contains the terms of reference and supersedes the Triennial Review guidance. A copy of the guidance can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tailored-reviews-of-public-bodies-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tailored-reviews-of-public-bodies-guidance</a></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:06:27.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524949/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524949/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Coal Authority: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when her Department plans to publish the terms of reference for its Triennial Review of the Coal Authority; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","40621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524950","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>We have not set out our plans in respect of biomass conversions. We will set out more details in relation to future Contracts for Difference (CfD) allocation rounds in due course.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-06-27T09:03:19.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524950/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524950/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 36652 on biofuel, whether her Department has undertaken to consider whether it is appropriate for biomass conversions to compete alongside offshore wind or the allocation pot for established technologies.","false","Biography information for Nigel Adams","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams","40628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524951","Department for Energy and Climate Change","true","2016-06-27","<p><del class="ministerial">At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">I refer the hon. Gentleman to the statement given by the Prime Minister on 24 June:</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-referendum-outcome-pm-statement-24-june-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-referendum-outcome-pm-statement-24-june-2016</a>.</ins></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-06-27T09:07:45.303Z","2016-06-27T12:21:41.413Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524951/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524951/answer","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524951/answer/previousversion/4383","Biography information for Amber Rudd","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Nuclear Power: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of a vote to leave the EU on the involvement of UK organisations in (a) the European Safeguards Research and Development Association and (b) the European Nuclear Safety Regulators Group.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","40602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524952","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-06-27","<p>I refer the hon. Gentleman to the statement given by the Prime Minister on 24 June:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-referendum-outcome-pm-statement-24-june-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/eu-referendum-outcome-pm-statement-24-june-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-06-27T10:36:58.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524952/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524952/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-06-14","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to the European Council decision of October 2014 on a Climate and Energy Policy Framework to set EU-wide energy targets for 2030, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of a vote to leave the EU on the UK (a) reducing greenhouse gas emissions by at least 40 per cent by 2030, (b) making the target for renewable energy at least 27 per cent and (c) meeting the indicative energy efficiency target of at least 27 per cent.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","40603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524953","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-29","<p>The UK supports ratification of the Cape Town agreement and will ratify when legal priorities allow, which is a matter for the Department of Transport. The UK already applies the 1993 Torremolinos Protocol relating to the Torremolinos International Convention for the Safety of Fishing Vessels through the Fishing Vessels (EC Directive on Harmonised Safety Regime) Regulations 1999.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government, through the Marine Management Organisation (MMO), has been at the forefront of international measures to tackle Illegal, Unreported and Unregulated (IUU) fishing, which remains a major threat, not just to the world’s fish stocks, but to its marine biodiversity and the livelihoods and security of coastal communities. The UK acts, alongside other European Union nations, to deny market access to products from IUU fishing, and to support third countries in developing their capability to detect and deter IUU fishing. Ground breaking work has also recently taken place between the MMO and UK based insurance companies to promote and encourage compliance with IUU regulations.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-29T10:52:48.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524953/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524953/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-14","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to (a) ratify the Cape Town agreement and (b) otherwise tackle illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing in the High Seas.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","40627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524954","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-27","<p>Under international rules set by the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), a hunting trophy from a species listed on Appendix I or Appendix II of the Convention can be exported only if the exporting country is satisfied that the hunt was both legal and sustainable.</p><p> </p><p>Importing controls are implemented at an EU-wide level and the UK works with other EU Member States to agree a collective approach. In light of growing concerns about the sustainability of the hunting of some species, stricter controls on the import of hunting trophies of six species, including lions and African elephants, have been introduced. As a result, the import of hunting trophies of certain species from certain countries is currently prohibited.</p><p> </p><p>The Government considers that properly managed, legal and sustainable trophy hunting can play a part in species conservation efforts, including by providing an important source of funding for conservation in some countries. In view of this, we have no plans to introduce legislation banning the import of all trophies of Appendix I and II species. We will however continue to monitor the impact of trophy hunting and will work to put in place greater protection, including prohibiting imports, if this is shown to be needed.</p><p> </p><p>For example, in recognition of the real concerns about the impact of trophy hunting on lion conservation, I announced in Parliament on 24 November 2015 that the Government will ban lion trophy imports by the end of 2017 unless there are improvements in the way hunting takes place in certain countries, judged against strict criteria. We will work with our European and international partners, and experts in the field, to reach a common approach to this issue.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-06-27T12:07:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524954/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524954/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-14","Animal Products: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to prohibit the import of trophies from any CITES  Appendix I or Appendix II listed species.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","40644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524955","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-28","<p>The Environment Agency advertised its proposed changes to the rod licence structure and duties on 6 May 2016 in the London Gazette, Welsh newspapers and in the angling press. The Environment Agency also consulted stakeholders through focus groups, newsletters, publications, websites, telephone calls and their stakeholder forum, the England Fisheries Group, prior to advertising the changes in England and Wales.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-28T10:50:11.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524955/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524955/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-14","Angling: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 19 January 2016 to Question 22080, when the Environment Agency will be consulting on the proposals to modernise the rod licence service.","true","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","40642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524956","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-06-27","<p>The UK Government does not fund ‘anti-beaching’ initiatives. However, it does fund the Cetacean Strandings Investigation Programme, the work of which is crucial in providing us with a better understanding of the general health of cetaceans in UK waters and the issues that affect them.</p><p>We are not aware of any countries identified as having ‘beaching hotspots’.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-06-27T10:33:59.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524956/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524956/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-06-14","Cetaceans: Beaches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 13 June 2016 to Question 39933, how much funding has been allocated to anti-beaching initiatives; and which countries have been identified as containing beaching hotspots.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","40493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-01","<p>The UK strongly believes that everyone, everywhere, should enjoy the rights and freedoms set out in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. We are concerned by any reports of violence perpetrated against people with albinism. Our High Commissioner to Malawi raised this issue during his meeting with the Malawian Foreign Minister on 27 April and we will continue to raise concerns about human rights violations and abuses in the region when the opportunities arise.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-07-01T11:43:40.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524957/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Sub-Saharan Africa: Albinism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will raise the issue of attacks on and murders of people with albinism with his counterparts in sub-Saharan African countries.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","40481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>I have repeatedly urged the Foreign Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Raymond Tshibanda, to ensure that elections in his country are open, transparent and are conducted in line with his country’s Constitution. Most recently I wrote to Mr Tshibanda in April this year to follow-up on my meeting with him in the margins of a UN debate on the Great Lakes region held in March 2016. I also met Mr Tshibanda at the African Union Summit in Addis Ababa in January 2016. In all my interactions with representatives of the Congolese Government I have stressed the importance of a peaceful, democratic transition of power in the DRC. My Hon Friend, the Member for Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner (Nick Hurd MP), Parliamentary Under-Secretary (Department for International Development), visited the DRC in March 2016.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-06-27T13:40:30.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524958/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Democratic Republic of Congo counterpart on ensuring that elections in that country are open and transparent.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524959","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-01","<p>[This question was tabled before the sad death of the Honourable Lady but the subject remains important and the Government’s response ought to be placed on the public record.]</p><p>The UN Secretary General’s annual report on Children in Armed Conflict was published on 2 June. The report includes a section outlining the impact of the conflict in Yemen on children.</p><p>The conflict in Yemen has had a significant impact on children, in terms of the numbers of child casualties, the recruitment of children as soldiers, and attacks on hospitals and schools.</p><p>We note the announcement by the UN Secretary General on 6 June that removed the listing of the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition from the report’s annex, pending the conclusion of a joint review by the UN and Saudi Arabia on the cases and numbers cited in the text. We welcome co-operation between the UN and Saudi Arabia to look in to this matter.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-01T11:46:02.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524959/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524959/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the constructive engagement of the Saudi-led coalition with the UN on the question of its de-listing as a state or armed group that violates children's rights during conflict.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","40580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524960","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are concerned about the recent extension of the imprisonment of Al Wefaq’s Secretary-General, Sheikh Ali Salman. We continue to raise his case with the Government of Bahrain, including most recently on 30 May when The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), raised his case at the highest levels during a visit to Manama. We understand there is a further stage in the legal process.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-27T13:05:06.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524960/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524960/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the prison sentence handed down to Sheikh Ali Salman; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524961","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","The UN publishes data on the number of people of UK origin living elsewhere, broken down by region and country. The dataset can be found at: http://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/estimates15.shtml","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-06-27T15:28:50.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524961/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524961/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the number of British nationals living (a) outside the UK and in the EU and (b) outside the UK and the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","40539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-04","The Government’s focus is on addressing the root causes of irregular migration so as to reduce the need for people to make perilous journeys to Europe. We have taken action to tackle smugglers and save lives at sea: HMS Enterprise is deployed as part of the EU’s counter migration operation, Operation Sophia. The UK has rescued almost 18,000 people, and disrupted suspected people smugglers, in the Mediterranean since 2015. At the G7 Summit in Japan on 27 May, the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), announced that the UK will work on a plan to boost the capability of the Libyan coastguard to stem the flow of illegal migration across the Mediterranean into Europe. Following adoption of the UN Security Council Resolution 2292 on 14 June, we are working with EU partners to ensure Op Sophia can begin its new taskings as soon as possible, including capacity building for the Libyan Coastguard. As the Prime Minister announced following the June European Council, RFA Mounts Bay will also be deployed to stop the flow of weapons to terrorists, particularly Daesh, in Libya. As the Prime Minister also said at the G7, the UK stands ready to deploy an additional naval vessel to the South Central Mediterranean.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-07-04T14:36:19.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524962/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the potential role of the UK in reducing the number of people trying to cross the Mediterranean in dangerous circumstances; and what plans he has to tackle the issue of deaths in the Mediterranean of people attempting to make that crossing.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","40520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524963","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are concerned about the recent extension of the imprisonment of Al Wefaq’s Secretary-General, Sheikh Ali Salman. We continue to raise his case with the Government of Bahrain, including most recently on 30 May when I raised his case at the highest levels during a visit to Manama. I understand there is a further stage in the legal process.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-06-27T14:01:53.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524963/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524963/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the government of Bahrain on the imprisonment of Sheikh Ali Salman in that country.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","40543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524964","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are seeking to establish the facts around the apparent prevention of a group of human rights activists travelling to Geneva for the for the UN Human Rights Council. I raised this issue with my Bahraini counterpart, Sheikh Khalid bin Ahmed Al Khalifa on 14 June 2016.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-06-27T14:03:19.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524964/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524964/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the government of Bahrain on recent travel bans imposed on Bahraini citizens.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","40544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are concerned about the recent re-arrest of Nabeel Rajab. The UK encourages Bahrain to respect the rights of all its citizens. We call on the Bahraini Government to act proportionately in all such cases to protect the universal rights of freedom of expression. I raised his case with my Bahraini counterpart, Sheikh Khalid Bin Ahmad Al Khalifa on 14 June 2016. We will continue to monitor his case as it develops.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-06-27T14:04:42.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524965/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524965/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Nabeel Rajab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Bahrain on the re-arrest of Nabeel Rajab in that country.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","40545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524966","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are concerned by the decision to suspend the activities of the Bahraini opposition group, Al Wefaq, and freeze its assets. I raised this issue with my Bahraini counterpart, Sheikh Khalid bin Ahmed Al Khalifa on 14 June 2016. We encourage Bahrain to respect the rights of political groups to operate and to seek an inclusive political dialogue.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-06-27T14:06:36.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524966/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524966/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Bahrain on the suspension of the main Shia opposition group in that country.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","40546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-01","<p>The release of some 200 political prisoners during its first few weeks in office is a strong demonstration of the new Burmese Government’s commitment to reforming human rights and the rule of law in Burma. However, we remain concerned that arrests, detentions and sentencing of political activists could continue while the military retains control of the Home Ministry, Police and Courts.</p><p>Tackling the causes of political prisoners will require a thorough but longer-term process of legislative and judicial reform. Having an effective Political Prisoners Committee will be an important element of that process and is something we have consistently called for and will continue to do.</p><p>The Government has long campaigned on the issue of political prisoners in Burma. We have maintained pressure through bilateral and international actions such as the two annual UN resolutions on Burma in which we have played an instrumental part. I raised this issue directly with the then Minister for the Presidency, U Aung Min, during my visit to Burma in July 2015. We will work with the new Government to help it continue to make progress.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-07-01T11:52:20.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524967/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524967/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Burma: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to his Burmese counterpart on (a) releasing people detained for the exercise of their human rights and (b) dropping charges pending against those who are facing imprisonment simply for the exercise of these rights.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524968","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-29","<p>A new five year Strategy for South Georgia &amp; the South Sandwich Islands, Strategy 2016 - 2020, was published in November 2015. The Strategy brings together HMG and the Government of South Georgia &amp; the South Sandwich Islands’ objectives. The Strategy aspires to world-class environmental management underpinned by the highest standards of governance, and sets out five strategic objectives. A copy of the Strategy can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://tinyurl.com/zfjbpn4" target="_blank">http://tinyurl.com/zfjbpn4</a></p><p>The FCO is currently working with the Ascension Island Government to identify the island’s infrastructure needs. This is the first step in identifying long-term requirements for Ascension.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-06-29T12:57:59.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524968/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524968/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Atlantic Ocean Islands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's five-year strategy and vision statement objectives are for (a) South Georgia and South Sandwich Islands and (b) Ascension Island.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","40622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-01","<p>[This question was tabled before the sad death of the Honourable Lady but the subject remains important and the Government’s response ought to be placed on the public record.]</p><p>The UN Secretary General’s annual report on Children in Armed Conflict was published on 2 June. The report includes a section outlining the impact of the conflict in Yemen on children.</p><p>The conflict in Yemen has had a significant impact on children, in terms of the numbers of child casualties, the recruitment of children as soldiers, and attacks on hospitals and schools.</p><p>We note the announcement by the UN Secretary General on 6 June that removed the listing of the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition from the report’s annex, pending the conclusion of a joint review by the UN and Saudi Arabia on the cases and numbers cited in the text. We welcome co-operation between the UN and Saudi Arabia to look in to this matter. A political solution remains the best way to bring this conflict and the suffering of the Yemeni people to an end. The UK Government continues to support the work of the United Nations on Children and Armed Conflict.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-07-01T11:47:55.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524969/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524969/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the temporary removal of the Saudi-led coalition from the UN's list of states and armed groups that violate children's rights during conflict on the integrity and effectiveness of UN Security Council measures on children and armed conflict.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","40581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524970","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>As of January 2016 149 full-time equivalent staff resource was spent on our Climate Change/Low Carbon Economy/Energy Security work across our network of 268 offices in 168 countries. Of these, 72 staff were working full-time on Climate Change and Energy issues.</p><p>As of June 2016 nine full-time equivalent staff in London work directly on climate change issues.</p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office allocation of resource is kept under regular review as staff and local priorities change, so there is a quite regular flux in numbers and locations. For example, in the run up to COP21, there was an increase in Ministerial and network engagement related to the Paris negotiations, to build support for a successful agreement.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-06-27T13:01:56.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524970/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524970/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many officials are employed in (a) his Department's London offices and (b) the UK's global diplomatic network work on climate security.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524971","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain, and call on the Bahraini Government to act proportionately in all such cases to protect the universal rights of freedom of expression and assembly. I most recently raised the issue of human rights on 2 June when I met with the Bahraini Foreign Minister at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-27T13:04:19.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524971/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524971/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Civil Liberties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on restrictions on freedom of assembly and expression in that country.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524972","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We regularly discuss human rights issues with the Government of Bahrain including the revocation of citizenship. I most recently raised the issue at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting, held in Bahrain on 2 June.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-06-27T13:02:44.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524972/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524972/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Bahrain: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the relocation of citizenship of Bahraini nationals.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524973","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-06-30","<p>The release of some 200 political prisoners during its first few weeks in office is a strong demonstration of the new Burmese Government’s commitment to reforming human rights and the rule of law in Burma. However, we remain concerned that arrests, detentions and sentencing of political activists could continue while the military retains control of the Home Ministry, Police and Courts.</p><p>Tackling the causes of political prisoners will require a thorough but longer-term process of legislative and judicial reform. Having an effective Political Prisoners Committee will be an important element of that process and is something we have consistently called for and will continue to do.</p><p>The Government has long campaigned on the issue of political prisoners in Burma. We have maintained pressure through bilateral and international actions such as the two annual UN resolutions on Burma in which we have played an instrumental part. I raised this issue directly with the then Minister for the Presidency, U Aung Min, during my visit to Burma in July 2015. We will work with the new Government to help it continue to make progress.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-06-30T15:11:35.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524973/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524973/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-06-14","Burma: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that the Burmese government relaunches the Prisoner of Conscience Affairs Committee or establishes a new Committee with a mandate to review the cases of people charged or deprived of their liberty for the exercise of their human rights.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","40597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524974","Department of Health","false","2016-06-29","<p>Information collected by the NHS Trust Development Authority showed that as of 31 March 2014 there were 961 staff engaged by National Health Service trusts within the scope of the HM Treasury guidance. Information collected by the Health and Social Care Information Centre indicated that at 31 March 2013 there were 1,267 such staff engaged by NHS foundation trusts (FTs).</p><p> </p><p>The numbers of Board off-payroll staff have declined consistently since the introduction of the HM Treasury guidance in August 2012. In 2012/13 there was a total of 2,403 engagements in trusts and FTs of which 200 were Board members or senior officials with significant financial responsibility. In 2013/14, there was a total of 2,070 of which 118 were Board members or senior officials with significant financial responsibility. In 2014/15, there were 1,193 in NHS trusts of which 52 were senior officials with significant financial responsibility. Figures for FTs in 2014/15 are not yet available. The Department continues to work with NHS Improvement to ensure that all off-payroll engagements comply with tax law and HM Treasury guidance.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-29T10:00:57.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524974/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524974/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","NHS: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 35252, how many staff within the scope of the HM Treasury guidance on senior off-payroll engagements were paid off-payroll in (a) NHS trusts in 2013-14 and (b) NHS foundation trusts in 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","40583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524975","Department of Health","false","2016-06-28","<p>NHS Improvement will publish this information as soon as possible.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-28T09:35:16.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524975/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524975/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","NHS: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 28 April 2016 to Question 35252, when he expects data to be published on the number of off-payroll staff within the scope of the HM Treasury guidance on senior off-payroll engagements in NHS foundation trusts in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","40584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524976","Department of Health","false","2016-06-28","<p>It is appreciated that we cannot achieve the transformation required without the active engagement of the organisations, clinicians and staff who actually deliver it, nor can we develop care integrated around the needs of patients and users without understanding what our communities want and without our partners in local government. Local areas are responsible for ensuring engagement with the most relevant organisations which may include university providers. From a workforce perspective, Health Education England are working across arm’s length bodies with Sustainability and Transformation Plan (STP) leads to ensure workforce and training requirements are considered through the STP process.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-06-28T16:02:40.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524976/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524976/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance (a) his Department and (b) NHS England have provided to Sustainability and Transformation footprint teams on involving university providers in the development of Sustainability and Transformation Plans.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524977","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>We are advised by NHS England that it is working closely with Health Education England to deliver the Capital Nurse programme.</p><p> </p><p>Impact on programmes such as the Capital Nurse programme, will be considered by NHS England once the outcome of the bursary consultation, which closes on 30 June 2016, has been published.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-27T14:08:27.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524977/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524977/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Nurses: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of ending the NHS bursary system on the Capital Nurse project in London.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524978","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>As part of the DH 2020 plan, the Department is making significant changes to the way it works. The Department’s approach is to flexibly access professional advice from a wide range of sources, including arm’s length bodies, regulators and professional bodies, rather than from a fixed standing team of internal advisers.</p><p> </p><p>These changes do not affect the role of the Chief Nursing Officer (CNO), who as CNO of the Department already advises, and will continue to advise all Ministers and the Department on the range of nursing issues.</p><p> </p><p>All staff in the Department, including staff in the current nursing, midwifery and allied health professions policy unit are eligible to apply for new roles in the organisation or to apply for a voluntary early severance scheme.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","40537 ; 40631","2016-06-27T13:57:57.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524978/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524978/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the effect on the role of chief nursing officer will be of the decision to abolish the nursing, midwifery and allied health professionals policy unit.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524979","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>The National Health Service will support women who have had female genital mutilation (FGM) and will provide them with appropriate care to ensure that cervical screening can be done as comfortably as possible, as for all women invited for cervical screening. FGM survivors may feel anxious about the procedure, and NHS staff are encouraged to have sensitive conversations with women about their worries.</p><p> </p><p>It is important that all women invited for screening attend appointments. Taking a cervical sample may not always be possible for women with FGM, and in such cases women can be referred to specialist gynaecological services who are trained in treating complications that can be caused by FGM.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","40641","2016-06-27T16:36:17.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524979/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524979/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that survivors of female genital mutilation are better protected from cervical cancer.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","40632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524980","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>As part of the DH 2020 plan, the Department is making significant changes to the way it works. The Department’s approach is to flexibly access professional advice from a wide range of sources, including arm’s length bodies, regulators and professional bodies, rather than from a fixed standing team of internal advisers.</p><p> </p><p>These changes do not affect the role of the Chief Nursing Officer (CNO), who as CNO of the Department already advises, and will continue to advise all Ministers and the Department on the range of nursing issues.</p><p> </p><p>All staff in the Department, including staff in the current nursing, midwifery and allied health professions policy unit are eligible to apply for new roles in the organisation or to apply for a voluntary early severance scheme.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","40537 ; 40630","2016-06-27T13:57:57.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524980/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524980/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Health Professions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for what reasons his Department discontinued the nursing, midwifery and allied health professionals policy unit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524981","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>As with all policy development to inform decision making the Government received and considered a range of representations from a number of stakeholders before and after the announcement in the Spending Review, 25 November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>These representations involved discussions with officials in the Department and from its arm’s length bodies, The Council of Deans of Health and Universities UK, Trade Unions, leading organisations including Royal Colleges, professional bodies and representatives from Universities.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-27T13:55:34.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524981/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524981/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which people and organisations his Department consulted (a) before and (b) after the announcement of 25 November 2015 to end NHS bursaries for nursing, midwifery and allied health professional students.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524982","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>Information on the number of secondary breast cancer nurses in England is not collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>It is for local National Health Service organisations with their knowledge of the healthcare needs of their local population to invest in training for specialist skills and to deploy specialist nurses.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-06-27T13:58:42.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524982/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524982/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Breast Cancer: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many secondary breast cancer nurses there are in England.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524983","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>As part of the DH 2020 plan, the Department is making significant changes to the way it works. The Department’s approach is to flexibly access professional advice from a wide range of sources, including arm’s length bodies, regulators and professional bodies, rather than from a fixed standing team of internal advisers.</p><p> </p><p>These changes do not affect the role of the Chief Nursing Officer (CNO), who as CNO of the Department already advises, and will continue to advise all Ministers and the Department on the range of nursing issues.</p><p> </p><p>All staff in the Department, including staff in the current nursing, midwifery and allied health professions policy unit are eligible to apply for new roles in the organisation or to apply for a voluntary early severance scheme.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","40630 ; 40631","2016-06-27T13:57:57.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524983/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524983/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Department of Health: Redundancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the potential number of redundancies which will result from the decision to abolish the nursing, midwifery and allied health professions policy unit.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","40537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524984","Department of Health","false","2016-06-27","<p>There are no changes in Government funding for children and adult mental health services planned.<strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Spending on mental health services is at record levels with an estimated spend of £11.7 billion in 2014/15. Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are also committed to increase their spending on mental health each year up to 2020 at least in line with the increase in their overall funding allocation. NHS England will be holding CCGs to account to ensure that this happens.</p><p> </p><p>We announced an additional £1 billion of investment for mental health over the next five years to deliver improvements in perinatal mental health, crisis care and liaison psychiatry.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also remains committed to investing £1.4 billion over the course of this Parliament to improve children and young people’s mental health. This includes the £1.25 billion announced in the March 2015 budget, which includes £75 million for perinatal mental health service, and the additional £150 million allocated in the 2014 Autumn Statement to improve community-based eating disorder services. £119 million of this overall investment has been allocated to CCGs in 2016-17 to transform local services through their Local Transformation Plans. It is for CCGs to decide how this funding should be used in collaboration with their local partners.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-06-27T14:33:21.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524984/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524984/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-06-14","Mental Health Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans additional changes in funding for child and adult mental health services.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","40521"
