"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525094","Home Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>We consider net migration of tens of thousands per year to be sustainable.</p><p>We will continue to work towards achieving the ambition to reduce net migration to sustainable levels over the course of this Parliament.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-27T14:45:16.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525094/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525094/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-14","European Fisheries Control Agency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 8 June (HL380), when they expect immigration to fall below 100,000 a year; and how they define "sustainable levels" of immigration.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525095","Home Office","false","2016-06-24","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls. To support the police in investigating cases of FGM, in March 2015 the College of Policing published Authorised Professional Practice and on 1 April we published updated multi-agency guidance on FGM for all professions, which we have put on a statutory footing to support compliance.</p><p>How the police enforce the law in any particular case is an operational matter. This is in line with their duties to keep the peace, protect communities and prevent the commission of offences, working within the provisions of the legal framework set by Parliament. It is for the police to decide what might assist them in that enforcement.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-24T12:56:06.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525095/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525095/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-14","European Chemicals Agency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to instigate targeted investigations into potential female genital mutilation perpetrators in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525096","Home Office","false","2016-06-28","<p>Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) is a crime and it is child abuse. We will not tolerate a practice that can cause extreme and lifelong physical and psychological suffering to women and girls.</p><p>We will not stop FGM until we have changed attitudes within communities. The Government works closely with a range of community organisations, faith groups and survivors through the Government’s FGM Unit. The FGM Unit carries out an ongoing programme of outreach with local community groups and professionals across England and Wales.</p><p>In 2014 we funded 29 community engagement projects across England and Wales, including a network of community champions, who are reaching thousands of women and girls who may be affected by FGM, and, importantly, their families.</p><p>In addition, the Department of Health’s £4m prevention programme is carrying out a range of work to improve the NHS response across England, and the Department for Education is providing up to £2m through its Innovation fund for work by the National FGM Centre to improve the social care response throughout England.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-06-28T16:13:55.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525096/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525096/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-14","European Institute for Gender Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether female genital mutilation campaigns are reaching communities outside London.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525097","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-28","<p>The commencement of commercial air services into St Helena Airport has been delayed due to wind shear and turbulence identified on the northern approach. Wind shear is an unpredictable phenomenon experienced at a number of airports around the world.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-28T15:10:11.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525097/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525097/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-14","European Defence Agency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who was responsible for the delay in opening the St Helena airport for commercial air services.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525098","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-28","<p>This is a matter for the St Helena Government and to our knowledge no claims for compensation have been received.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-28T15:10:24.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525098/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525098/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-14","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to consider compensation claims from those who can prove they have incurred losses due to the delay in the St Helena airport becoming operational.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525099","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-28","<p>A number of options are being explored. The aim is to establish scheduled services once an operator is identified and regulatory conditions are met.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-28T15:07:03.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525099/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525099/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525099/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-14","Chronic Fatigue Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect regular commercial air services to operate from St Helena airport.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525100","Department for International Development","false","2016-06-28","<p>In order to retain access for the people of St Helena, the St Helena Government has extended the services of the RMS St Helena for a further period beyond its previously planned service end date of July 2016. This is until September 2016 in the first instance but will be kept under review.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-06-28T15:09:57.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525100/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525100/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525100/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-06-14","Holiday Accommodation: Fire Prevention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they propose to reinstate RMS St Helena for passenger services, and if so, when and for how long.","false","Biography information for Lord Foulkes of Cumnock",,"Lord Foulkes of Cumnock","HL686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525102","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-28","<p>A full impact assessment for the Common Reporting Standard (CRS) was published at Budget 2015 in a Tax Information and Impact Note (TIIN).</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has estimated that between 500 and 8,000 of the more than 165,000 charities in the UK could be affected by the CRS. Precise estimates of the overall cost are difficult to make given the upfront costs to charities is still uncertain.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no assessment of the impact on grant recipients.</p><p> </p><p>Including charities is vital to create true transparency in the international tax system, which ultimately benefits taxpayers through reduced tax evasion and avoidance.</p><p> </p><p>In the UK the charity sector is well regulated, but this is not the case elsewhere around the world. If another jurisdiction excluded charities this would allow a simple method for evaders to escape reporting –significantly impacting the UK's inbound data and hence the predicted yield from the CRS.</p><p> </p><p>As signatories to this global standard, the UK has agreed to the definitions that will include charities where they have predominantly investment income. To make the CRS an effective tool in tackling evasion, and show the benefits to the UK taxpayer, the UK must adhere to the global standard – including on charities - in order that we can expect our international partners to do likewise.</p><p> </p><p>Automatic exchange agreements are expected to raise over £0.5 billion over the five-year scorecard period. This amount has been updated from the original TIIN after a review by the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL688","2016-06-28T11:39:03.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525102/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525102/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525102/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Holiday Accommodation: Fire Prevention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what regulatory impact assessment they have conducted in relation to the implementation of the Automatic Exchange of Financial Account Information in Tax Matters via the OECD Common Reporting Standard, and what were the conclusions of that assessment with regard to its effect on charities and their grant recipients.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525103","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-28","<p>A full impact assessment for the Common Reporting Standard (CRS) was published at Budget 2015 in a Tax Information and Impact Note (TIIN).</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has estimated that between 500 and 8,000 of the more than 165,000 charities in the UK could be affected by the CRS. Precise estimates of the overall cost are difficult to make given the upfront costs to charities is still uncertain.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no assessment of the impact on grant recipients.</p><p> </p><p>Including charities is vital to create true transparency in the international tax system, which ultimately benefits taxpayers through reduced tax evasion and avoidance.</p><p> </p><p>In the UK the charity sector is well regulated, but this is not the case elsewhere around the world. If another jurisdiction excluded charities this would allow a simple method for evaders to escape reporting –significantly impacting the UK's inbound data and hence the predicted yield from the CRS.</p><p> </p><p>As signatories to this global standard, the UK has agreed to the definitions that will include charities where they have predominantly investment income. To make the CRS an effective tool in tackling evasion, and show the benefits to the UK taxpayer, the UK must adhere to the global standard – including on charities - in order that we can expect our international partners to do likewise.</p><p> </p><p>Automatic exchange agreements are expected to raise over £0.5 billion over the five-year scorecard period. This amount has been updated from the original TIIN after a review by the Office for Budget Responsibility.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL687","2016-06-28T11:39:03.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525103/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525103/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/525103/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-14","Holiday Accommodation: Fire Regulations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the costs of compliance for charities in implementing the Automatic Exchange of Financial Account Information in Tax Matters via the OECD Common Reporting Standard compared with the intended benefits for the taxpayer.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL688"
