"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524648","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-21","<p>The Gazette (<a href="https://www.thegazette.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.thegazette.co.uk/</a>) is the UK’s official public record and is published by Authority. First printed in 1665, The Gazette has evolved into a sophisticated online digital platform that is accessed and used by tens of thousands of commercial organisations, local and central government, and the general public, every day.</p><p>Some notices are required by statute to be published in The Gazette, whilst others are placed voluntarily, to put official information permanently on the public record and in the public domain, including state notices such as the Queen’s Birthday and New Year Honours; insolvency notices such as bankruptcy and winding up orders; legal notices relating to probate and deceased estates; public sector notices; and other notices such as the dissolution of companies or recording a change of name by deed poll.</p><p>Today, most people access and use The Gazette online. Online access to all published notices (including an archive of notices) is free, and users can easily download a pdf of the latest Gazette and print it for free. Libraries get a free pdf copy which they can make available for readers to view or print. Additionally, printed copies can be ordered from The Stationery Office at a small cost.</p><p>The London Gazette has an average daily print run of 114 copies. The Belfast Gazette has an average weekly print run of 91. The Edinburgh Gazette is printed twice a week, and has an average print run of 165. The publicly procured concession contract under which the Gazette is produced is subject to commercial confidentiality. A link to the contract can be found at <a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/749253/" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/749253/</a>.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-21T12:13:04.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524648/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524648/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Cabinet Office: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many copies of The Gazette at what cost are printed each day.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","40336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524649","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>I chair an inter-ministerial group on Clean Growth, which considers issues relating to air quality and de-carbonisation, where these have a cross-departmental aspect. The group meets as and when required and its members include ministers and officials from the relevant departments, including Defra, DECC, DfT, DCLG and BIS.</p><p>To protect the integrity of the policy-making progress, we do not comment on the specific timing or agendas of cabinet committees or inter-ministerial groups.</p><p> </p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-06-27T07:20:29.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524649/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524649/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-13","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings of the Inter-Ministerial Group on Clean Growth have discussed the fifth carbon budget since November 2015; and which departments have been involved in those meetings.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","40408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524650","Home Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The Home Office is answering this question as the lead department for CBRN(e) Response. The Home Office and its partners use a range of evidence to develop the UK’s response to CBRN(e) incidents. This information has informed the development of the Initial Operational Response which has been rolled out nationally across the emergency services. The booklet produced under the auspices of the PRACTICE EU project and referred to in the oral evidence is based on the same body of evidence as the UK response and consequently its content is consistent with our approach.”</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-06-16T11:39:53.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524650/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524650/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-06-13","Emergency Services: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Civil Contingencies Unit has made an assessment of the implications for its CBRNE defense policies of the findings of the PRACTICE EU project on the different public reactions to industrial or transport accidents and terrorist incidents, referred to in oral evidence to the Science and Technology Committee on 7 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","40413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524651","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>The proposal is for the Centre to be located in a major international financial centre such as London.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-16T15:05:31.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524651/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524651/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524651/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-13","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, where the planned International Anti-Corruption Coordination Centre will be based.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524652","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave him on 6 June 2016 to UIN: 38864.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-16T15:02:55.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524652/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524652/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524652/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-13","Anti-corruption Ministerial Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on what date the Inter-Ministerial Group on Corruption last met.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524653","Cabinet Office","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Anti-Corruption Champion is not paid a salary for that role.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-06-27T07:18:44.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524653/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524653/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524653/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-06-13","Anti-corruption Champion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Anti-Corruption Champion is paid a salary for that role.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","40277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524654","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-27","<p>This Government invested in HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC) Stamp Taxes business unit at Budget 2016 to increase capacity in relation to the new higher rates of Stamp Duty Land Tax on additional properties.</p><p> </p><p>In order to reduce volumes of correspondence HMRC is reviewing guidance to cover those areas where substantial correspondence has been generated.</p><p> </p><p>Additional resources have been put into call handling at HMRC’s Stamp Taxes helpline, providing an improved customer service and aiming to reduce follow-up correspondence.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-06-27T10:30:00.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524654/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524654/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524654/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce the amount of correspondence not yet dealt with at the HM Revenue and Customs Stamp Duty office.","false","Biography information for Gordon Henderson","Sittingbourne and Sheppey","Gordon Henderson","40407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524655","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-21","<p>If the Government were to use total household income as the criteria for the High Income Child Benefit Charge on households, this would require collecting information of the incomes of everyone in each of the eight million households receiving Child Benefit. This would effectively introduce a new means test. The Government’s approach withdraws Child Benefit from those on high incomes, whilst having no impact on the majority of claimants.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-21T12:48:14.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524655/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524655/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524655/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","Child Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons the income of the highest-earning parent is used to assess eligibility for child benefit rather than the joint incomes of both parents.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","40400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524656","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-20","The Treasury continuously monitors global economic developments, including in China, and their impact on the UK as part of the normal process of policy development. As one of the most open trading economies in the world with a large financial sector, we have to recognise that the UK is not immune to the continued problems being experienced in the world economy. Nonetheless, the Bank of England’s 2015 stress tests modelled a severe slowdown in commodities and emerging markets. No banks were required to submit revised capital plans following the stress tests. These results indicate that the UK banking system would have the capacity to continue to lend to the real economy, even under such a severe adverse scenario.","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-20T12:30:00.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524656/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524656/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524656/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","Debts: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect on the UK economy of the increase in corporate debt in China.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","40326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524657","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-20","<p>HMRC receives enquiries from hon. Members about tax credit awards in a number of different ways. HMRC seeks to answer every one as a high priority.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC collates internal management statistics relating to tax credit enquiries but does not hold comprehensive figures as to how many of these were submitted by hon. Members via each medium.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-20T11:56:08.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524657/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524657/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524657/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many enquiries have been made by hon. Members to HM Revenue and Customs on tax credits claims by (a) e-mail, (b) telephone and (c) letter in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","40335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524658","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-27","<p>NS&amp;I and Atos regularly review the mix of where roles are undertaken so as to best meet the needs of the business. There are no current plans to move roles in the UK undertaken by employees of Atos off-shore.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-06-27T10:36:15.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524658/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524658/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524658/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","National Savings and Investments: Offshoring","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 26 May 2016 to Question 38066, what the (a) number, (b) current responsibilities and (c) current locations are of any National Savings and Investment roles undertaken by employees of Atos which are planned to be off-shored.","true","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","40453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524659","HM Treasury","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Treasury has made no formal estimate of the impact on the public finances resulting from the effects of supported housing provision on the life chances of residents. However, analysis of the financial benefits of capital investment in specialist housing has previously been commissioned by the Homes and Communities Agency: Financial benefits of investment in specialist housing for vulnerable and older people (2010). This includes analysis of the impact of capital funding for specialist housing on the usage and associated costs of wider public services, including primary and secondary healthcare, social care, the criminal justice system, and the benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions and Department for Communities and Local Government are currently conducting an evidence review of the supported housing sector, which will report shortly.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-06-27T10:41:46.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524659/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524659/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524659/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-06-13","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the effect on the public purse of the effects on the life chances of residents of the services and support provided through supported housing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","40419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524660","Church Commissioners","false","2016-06-15","<p>The Church Commissioners have no plans to undertake such an assessment.</p><p>Through its network of parishes and dioceses the Church of England is present in all the communities of England. The clergy and people of the Church of England are well placed to hear, articulate and respond to the needs and concerns of local communities. This plays an important role in informing the public engagement of the Church on social policy matters especially at local level.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Mrs Caroline Spelman",,"2016-06-15T14:45:40.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524660/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524660/answer",,,,,"9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2016-06-13","Church of England: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, if the Church of England will make an assessment of the effect of austerity on communities in the most deprived areas as measured by the English Indices of Deprivation 2015.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","40353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524661","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-16","<p>Between January and March 2016, local planning authorities decided 82 per cent of major applications on time; the highest figure on record.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-06-16T17:31:38.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524661/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524661/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524661/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-13","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of local authorities in processing and deciding planning applications within recommended timescales.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","40381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524662","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-06-27","<p>The Government submitted an initial UK application to the European Union Solidary Fund on Friday 26 February. The application included an estimate of eligible costs of direct damage incurred by the storms in December and early January. Since making this initial application we have continued to refine our cost estimates. I will update Parliament once the European Commission’s final assessment has been made.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-06-27T15:47:30.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524662/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524662/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524662/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-06-13","Floods: Lake District","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when he expects his Department to submit a final estimate of the damage caused by flooding in the South Lakes area to the European Commission as part of the UK's application to the EU Solidarity Fund.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","40274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524663","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-06-20","<p>Expenditure on the main DWP working age benefits, including Housing Benefit, for European Economic Area (EEA) national-led claims can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502129/benefit-expenditure-eea-nationals-ad-hoc-stats.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/502129/benefit-expenditure-eea-nationals-ad-hoc-stats.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-06-20T09:21:18.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524663/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524663/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524663/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-06-13","Housing Benefit: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of housing benefit payments is made to non-British nationals in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Reynolds","Stalybridge and Hyde","Jonathan Reynolds","40442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524664","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>The most recent assessment was made by the independent regulator, Ofcom, in their report: The Future of Free to View TV (May 2014). This is a fast moving market and as it evolves, the Government will keep these issues under review.<br><br>Detailed spectrum planning is a matter for Ofcom.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","40425","2016-06-27T14:24:20.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524664/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524664/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524664/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of moving television from broadcast spectrum to other delivery mechanisms.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","40428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524665","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>Ofcom had commissioned a study in 2015 into the sensitivity of mobile handsets. The study can be found here: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/other/technology-research/2015-reports/mobile-handset-testing/" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/market-data-research/other/technology-research/2015-reports/mobile-handset-testing/</a></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-27T14:25:56.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524665/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524665/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524665/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of telephone design on whether the mobile coverage detailed in Ofcom's published maps of coverage is attainable.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","40424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524666","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>The most recent assessment was made by the independent regulator, Ofcom, in their report: The Future of Free to View TV (May 2014). This is a fast moving market and as it evolves, the Government will keep these issues under review.<br><br>Detailed spectrum planning is a matter for Ofcom.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","40428","2016-06-27T14:24:20.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524666/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524666/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524666/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish a long-term spectrum plan for broadcast television.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","40425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524667","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","As part of the Government's wider work to improve digital connectivity the Government announced a package of planning reforms on 17 March to support the rollout of digital infrastructure so that UK consumers can continue to benefit from the opportunities offered by digital economy. We would encourage mobile infrastructure providers to consider sharing infrastructure wherever possible.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-27T14:34:33.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524667/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524667/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524667/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of common coverage planning for mobile services similar to that undertaken by the broadcast industry.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","40426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524668","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-27","<p>The privacy aspects of this issue are regulated under the Data Protection Act (DPA). Compliance with the DPA is regulated and enforced by the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) which maintains guidance relating to the Act. ICO guidance for app developers on privacy in mobile apps is available here: <a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/online-and-apps/" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/online-and-apps/</a> (PDF document here:<a href="https://ico.org.uk/media/for-organisations/documents/1596/privacy-in-mobile-apps-dp-guidance.pdf" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/media/for-organisations/documents/1596/privacy-in-mobile-apps-dp-guidance.pdf</a>)</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-27T14:35:49.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524668/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524668/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524668/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","ICT: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department or Ofcom has made of the effect on consumers of data leakage (a) between applications on a consumer device and (b) between a consumer's device and application servers.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","40427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524669","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-06-20","<p>Superfast broadband with speeds of at least 24Mbps is now available to 90 per cent of UK premises and this will reach 95 per cent by December 2017. The Government has also implemented a basic broadband scheme to enable all premises to gain access to speeds of at least 2Mbps. This enables residents and businesses in all parts of the UK to gain access to every government service available online.</p><p> </p><p>In addition it is the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation that will give people the legal right to request a broadband connection, no matter where they live, by the end of this Parliament. Our ambition is that this should initially be set at 10 Mbps.</p><p> </p><p>There is no specific recommended speed advised by Ofcom.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-06-20T11:13:55.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524669/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524669/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524669/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-06-13","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, in how many local authority areas in (a) London and (b) England broadband speeds are below the recommended speed as advised by Ofcom.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","40317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524670","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>Following its establishment in April 2015, 77th Brigade is planned to reach full operating capability in December 2019.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:01:23.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524670/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524670/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether 77th Brigade's full operating capability has been met.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40346"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524671","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>Russia is just one of a wide range of different nations that elements of 77th Brigade are studying in order to develop a deep understanding of their approach to operations. The focus is on specific aspects of these countries' operational concepts and doctrine including information warfare and the use of non-military means.</p><p>As is normal for operational deployments overseas, personnel will only deploy once they have met standards laid down for each theatre by the Joint Commander.</p><p>There are currently 141 reserve personnel serving with 77th Brigade.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:06:39.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524671/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524671/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what expertise on Russia is required of members of the 77th Brigade; what the operational deployment standards are of that brigade; and how many members of that brigade were recruited from the Reserves.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524672","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>77th Brigade includes 10 members of the Naval Service (Royal Navy and Royal Marines) and 11 Royal Air Force personnel.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:01:54.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524672/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524672/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many members of the (a) Royal Navy and (b) Royal Air Force are deployed to the 77th Brigade.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524673","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>77th Brigade does not specifically select personnel for language capability. However, personnel within the brigade hold 59 'standard level profile' (GCSE - to master's degree level) qualifications in languages including Dari, Pashtu, Russian and Urdu. Some personnel hold more than one of these qualifications.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:02:33.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524673/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524673/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which languages to what level members of the 77th Brigade speak.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524674","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>Doctrine provides the philosophy and enduring principles by which military forces guide their actions. 77th Brigade uses a combination of NATO and UK doctrine including for Civil Military Cooperation, Security, Stabilisation, Information and Media Operations, as well as Peace Support and Humanitarian Assistance<em>.</em></p><p>The doctrine applied by 77th Brigade has been developed through collaboration with NATO allies, within the UK military and with other Government Departments. It will also have called on the experience and expertise of other nations and academia. The doctrine is dynamic, being constantly tested against experience, and crafted for a contemporary environment, and will therefore continue to develop as new or anticipated challenges appear.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:01:51.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524674/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524674/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the doctrine and concepts are of the 77th Brigade; and how those doctrines and concepts were developed.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524675","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-06-20","<p>None.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-06-20T14:01:01.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524675/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/524675/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-06-13","Armed Forces: Information Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he has had with his (a) US counterpart and (b) other NATO counterparts on the role of the 77th Brigade.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","40344"
